Mr. Gore is a 57-year-old male from Toledo, Ohio.  Interestingly, I evaluated his wife, Mrs. Tracy R. Gore, recently for rectal cancer.  She underwent a coloanal anastomosis in December 2009 with a diverting loop ileostomy and approximately a month ago returned for ileostomy closure by Dr. Jesse Gomez.  She is doing well.  With his wife's recent rectal cancer and as he had not undergone colonoscopy screening, he went in for a colonoscopy on April 12, 2010, and was found to have a 50% circumferential lesion at 16 cm. This was tattooed.  Biopsies were performed and reviewed here consistent with invasive grade 3 of 4 adenocarcinoma.  The biopsy specimen says it was located at 18 cm but the colonoscopy report says 16 cm.  A local CT-scan of the abdomen and pelvis dated April 12, 2010, has been reviewed revealing thickening and inflammation of the distal sigmoid colon consistent with his malignancy without lymphadenopathy.  He had a 6-mm low-density lesion in the right hepatic lobe that is indeterminate.  A local CEA on April 12, 2010, was 2.8.
Mr. Gore has noticed for the last six-months that his bowels have been a little bit on the looser side.  He moves them three times a day in the morning, and this has been stable for him.  He denies fecal incontinence.  No abdominal or rectal pain.  His weight has been stable.  He has been more fatigued for about the last 16 months and initially went in for evaluation of fatigue in January 2009 to his local provider.  He had a treadmill test which was normal.  He has no family history of colorectal cancer.  He had not had rectal bleeding until today. For the first-time he noticed bright-red hematochezia.  A CBC at-home was normal.

